AGI - Asia was "the region to the world most affected by climate disasters" in 2023>, with floods and storms that caused the greatest number of victims and economic losses. The United Nations World Meteorological Organization is known in its annual report. "Climate change has exacerbated the frequency and severity of such events, > profoundly affecting societies, economies and, above all, human lives and the environment in which we live", said Celeste Saul, OMM director at a press conference. 2023 was the hottest year ever recorded worldwide, but in Asia the impact of hot waves is becoming increasingly serious, emphasizes the OMM, adding that melting of glaciers - especially in the Himalayan chain - puts at risk the water security of the region.
&nbsp;
In addition, Asia is heating faster than the global average >, with temperatures last year almost two degrees Celsius higher than the average from 1961 to 1990. "The results of the report reflect," said OMM number one. "Many countries in the region have lived the hottest year ever recorded in 2023, accompanied by a series of extreme conditions, from drought and hot waves to floods and storms," the report states. The report on the state of Asia 2023 highlights the accelerated pace of the main indicators of climate change, such as surface temperature, glacier retreat and rising sea level, stating that they would have serious impacts on the societies, economies and ecosystems of the region.
&nbsp;
The average annual temperature close to the surface > of Asia in 2023 was the second highest ever recorded, with 0,91 degrees Celsius over the average period 1991-2020 and 1.87 degrees Celsius over the average period 1961-1990.&nbsp; particularly high average temperatures were recorded by western Siberia to central Asia and from eastern China to Japan, the report states. Japan has lived the hottest summer ever recorded. As for rainfall, they were lower than the Himalayas norm and the Hindu Kush mountain range in Pakistan and Afghanistan. Meanwhile, southwestern China has suffered from drought, with levels of rainfall below the norm in almost every month of the year.
&nbsp;
The Asian region of high mountain, centered on the Tibetan plateau, contains the largest volume of ice outside the polar regions. In recent decades, most of these glaciers have retired, and this has happened at an accelerated pace, according to OMM data: 20 of the 22 monitored glaciers in the region showed continuous mass loss last year. The report also states that the sea surface temperatures in the Northwest Pacific Ocean in 2023 were the highest ever recorded. Last year, 79 disasters were reported in Asia associated with hydrological risks. Of these, more than 80% were floods and storms, which caused more than 2,000 deaths. Nine million people were directly affected. "The floods were by far the main cause of death among the events reported in 2023", emphasizes the OMM, detecting the persistent high level of vulnerability of Asia to natural risk events.
&nbsp;
Following a typhoon, Hong Kong recorded 158.1 millimeters of rainfall in an hour on September 7, 2023, a record since the recordings began in 1884. The OMM states that it is urgent that national weather services in the region produce data to better alert risks. "It is essential that our actions and strategies reflect the urgency of this moment," says Saul. "Reducing greenhouse gas emissions and adapting to climate change is a fundamental necessity." &nbsp;

