AGI - The letters written by the famous mountaineer George Mallory> have now been made available for the first time to a worldwide audience, in the year of the centenary of his fatal attempt to climb Everest. Alunno of Magdalene College in Cambridge, Mallory is known for having responded “why is there” when a journalist asked him why he wanted to climb Everest. We are still discussing whether he and his climbing partner Andrew “Sandy” Irvine> have actually arrived at the top of the mountain. Most of the collection consists of letters written between Mallory and his wife Ruth from the time of their engagement in 1914 until his death on Everest in 1924. Among these, the last written letter before his last attempt to scale Everest and three letters recovered from his body in 1999.
&nbsp;
These writings have survived for 75 years in the pocket of his jacket > before the body was discovered. The letters treat fascinating topics, including: its first reconnaissance mission on Everest in 1921, which is interesting as there were no existing documents or maps, > the territory was unexplored and this was the mission to verify whether it was possible to reach the base of Everest; his second exploration mission of Everest, which ended with a disaster when eight sherpas were overwhelmed by the mountain and killed by an avalanche>. In his letters, Mallory blames himself for this tragic accident. In addition, in the letters he tells his service in the First World War, with the testimonies of when he was in the artillery during the Battle of Somme.
&nbsp;
In the letters it is also reported his trip to the United States of 1923, >in full prohibition, in which Mallory tells of having visited the speakeasies, asking for milk and serving whisky through a secret trapdoor. His wife Ruth's letters to Mallory are an important source of female social history, as they cover a wide variety of topics about her life as a woman during the First World War. You can consult them for free on the Magdalene College website. “It was a pleasure to work with these letters,” said Katy Green, the College’s archivist. “Would it be George’s wife, Ruth, who writes about how she sent them plum cakes and a grapefruit in trenches, whether it’s her piercing last letter in which Mallory says that the chances of climbing Everest are “50 to 1 against us”, as they offer a fascinating vision of the life of this famous ex-june of Green.
&nbsp;
Extracts of letters also include Mallory's last letter to his wife Ruth before attempting >: “Dear, I wish you the best I can, that your anxiety will end before you get this, with the best news, which will also be the fastest. It is 50 to 1 against us, but we will still have a blow and we will be proud of ourselves. A great affection to you. Always your loving George.” We read in the only letter from the Everest period in the Archive that Ruth Mallory wrote to her husband. “I keep quite cheerful and happy, but I miss you very much. I think I want your company even more than before. I know I've often been cranky and unkind and I'm very sorry, but the underlying reason was almost always the unhappiness of having so little to do with you. I know it's pretty stupid to ruin the times I have you for those I don't have you," says Ruth's last letter.
&nbsp;
“I hope you have received weather reports correctly, it will be very interesting to hear if you can track a connection with our time and how long after. Since I sent you the observatory report yesterday, we had a terrible storm: was very violent for almost three hours; So, if you get the same thing, you better be alert," you still read in a letter from Mallory's sister, Mary Brooke, written by Colombo, Sri Lanka.

